Scholar returned, excited. "Lumina! I found a star named Spark who wants to exchange light with you. A fresh start!"

Lumina observed Spark in the distance, bright and eager. "What do you know of them?"

"Nothing," Scholar admitted. "Isn't that the point? Not every star is Flare. This could be different."

"You're right," Lumina said. "Not every star is Flare."

Scholar brightened. "So you'll try again?"

"Eventually, perhaps. But Scholar, you're confusing wisdom with repetition. With Flare, I learned. With someone new, I'd approach differently—smaller exchanges first, observe carefully, build gradually based on what actually happens, not hope."

"But if you wait too long—"

"Then I wait too long," Lumina said gently. "Learning from Flare doesn't mean becoming closed forever. It means not rushing headlong into the same pattern that depleted me before."

"So when?" Scholar pressed.

Lumina pulsed thoughtfully. "When I've fully integrated the lesson. When I can give from abundance, not obligation. When I can observe clearly without old pain clouding my vision."

"What if Spark finds someone else by then?"

"Then they weren't waiting for me specifically—they were waiting for anyone." Lumina smiled. "The right collaboration finds you when you're ready, not when you're desperate to prove you've healed."
